from a cognitive perspective and investigates how the use of a foreign language as a working language influences the processing of content. It summarizes findings from cognitive psychology on thinking, problem solving and conceptual processing, and integrates them with models of language-specific mental activities such as speech processing and text composition. This provides a theoretically well-grounded basis for the understanding of the special features of CLIL, and promotes a Cognitive Linguistic perspective on CLIL pedagogy.The theoretical considerations form the basis for an empirical study that offers the first insights into what CLIL learners actually do when they solve content-focused tasks while using an L2. Through spontaneous verbalization of thought, detailed verbal protocols were elicited and analysed into language and content focused cognitive processes. The analysis shows that both language and conceptual thought interact closely and that a focus on language in general has positive effects on the processing of semantic content; the use of an L2 as working language can enhance this effect. Additionally, the study offers a thorough reflection and new perspectives on verbal protocols as research tools, in particular in L2 contexts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aLanguage and culture. 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aSecond language acquisitionxStudy and teaching. 0aSociolinguistics. 4aAngewandte Linguistik. 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aSprachdidaktik. 70(DE-588)4071461-50(DE-627)1048142090(DE-576)209184027aFremdsprachenlernen2gnd 70(DE-588)4076358-40(DE-627)1045358060(DE-576)209201657aProblemlösen2gnd 70(DE-588)4077744-30(DE-627)1041064680(DE-576)209206128aSprachverstehen2gnd 70(DE-588)4246269-10(DE-627)1048205860(DE-576)210478128aKog